  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I see the saved Wi-Fi passwords on my mobile?",
  "response": "To view saved Wi-Fi passwords on your mobile device, the process varies depending on whether you're using an Android or iOS device. Here's how you can do it on each platform:\n\n### **Android**\n1. **Using Android Settings (Android 10 and above):**\n   - Go to **Settings** > **Network & Internet** > **Wi-Fi**.\n   - Tap on the Wi-Fi network you're connected to or have previously saved.\n   - Tap on the **Share** or **QR Code** option (you might need to authenticate with your PIN, password, or fingerprint).\n   - The Wi-Fi password will be displayed in the QR code or shareable text.\n\n2. **Using a File Explorer (Rooted Android):**\n   - If your device is rooted, you can use a file explorer app like **ES File Explorer** or **Root Explorer** to navigate to the following file:\n     ```\n     /data/misc/wifi/wpa_supplicant.conf\n     ```\n   - Open the file, and you'll see the list of saved Wi-Fi networks along with their passwords.\n\n3. **Using Third-Party Apps (Non-Rooted Android):**\n   - Apps like **WiFi Password Viewer** or **WiFi Key Recovery** can display saved Wi-Fi passwords if your device is rooted.\n\n---\n\n### **iOS**\n1. **Using iCloud Keychain:**\n   - iOS does not allow direct viewing of saved Wi-Fi passwords on the device itself.\n   - You can access saved Wi-Fi passwords on a Mac synced with your iCloud Keychain:\n     - On your Mac, go to **System Preferences** > **Network** > **Wi-Fi**.\n     - Click **Advanced**, select the Wi-Fi network, and click **Show Password**.\n     - Authenticate with your Mac\u2019s password, and the Wi-Fi password will be displayed.\n\n2. **Using Third-Party Apps (Jailbroken iOS):**\n   - If your iPhone is jailbroken, you can use apps like **WiFi Passwords** from Cydia to view saved Wi-Fi passwords.\n\n---\n\n### **Important Notes**\n- **Security:** Viewing saved Wi-Fi passwords may require authentication to ensure only authorized users can access this information.\n- **Rooting/Jailbreaking:** Rooting or jailbreaking your device can void warranties and expose your device to security risks. Proceed with caution.\n- **Backup:** Always back up your device before making any significant changes.\n\nLet me know if you need further assistance!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
